        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10211",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "More info here:  http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/developer\/ticket\/3",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-06-29T13:15:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-06-29T13:15:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10239",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I believe the default should be \"PDO::CASE_NATURAL\".\nI think we should leave column names as returned by the database driver, so that developers have access to this information (i.e. the case), if needed.  Simple principle of preserving data.  If data is not captured and preserved, it is not available.  If data is available, it can always be ignored, or normalized (e.g. strtolower).\n\nHowever, we need to make certain that all existing code expecting lower-cased column names won't break (i.e. strtolower).",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-06-30T15:57:53.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-06-30T15:57:53.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10604",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "READ http:\/\/dev.mysql.com\/doc\/refman\/5.0\/en\/name-case-sensitivity.html  BEFORE COMMENTING ON THIS ISSUE.\n\nWe can not use either PDO_CASE_LOWER or PDO_CASE_UPPER and remain \"case-preserving\".  If the ZF does not support preserving the case, then integration with existing database would become much more difficult, and also precludes new projects from using camelCase (e.g. camelCase with Hungarian notation).\n\nSomeone needs to review *all* Zend_Db* code and determine the extent of effort required to preserve case, without forcing all developers using lowercase table and column names to change their existing application code.   Note, it is possible for some databases (including MySQL) to allow interaction with the database using lowercase column and table names, while the actual names in the database are mixed case.\n\nThus, a forward and reverse mapping hash table presents one possible approach, where keys and values are lowercased and natural-cased table\/column names.  Performance issues must be carefully considered.  For example, when and where should names be dynamically normalized (to lowercase)?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-07-25T14:21:53.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-07-25T14:21:53.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10689",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Copied from Simon's ZF-301 issue:\n{quote}\nApart from providing a more code-friendly appearance, I feel that the camelcaps transform on field names creates another unnecessary layer of abstraction. If my database has user_list_id and member_status, it is far more readable and understandable for those looking through the code to refer to the field names as-is. Especially as the insert\/update and where criteria code still relies on the 'uncamelised' id, this treatment seems a bit inconsistent and redundant, considering the inflector that is needed to re-transform them back to the original field name.\n\nI'm not saying to ditch this feature (as I'm sure some people do quite like this), however wish it to be a configurable option. Ideally you would enable\/disable when you instantiate the Db object.\n{code}\n$params = array ('host'     => '127.0.0.1',\n                 'username' => 'malory',\n                 'password' => '******',\n                 'dbname'   => 'camelot',\n                 'transform' => Zend_Db::CASE_DEFAULT);\n\n$db = Zend_Db::factory('PDO_MYSQL', $params);\n{code}\nCASE_DEFAULT = Unchanged\nCASE_MIXED = Uppercase words (Camel style - strip underscores)\nCASE_LOWER = Lowercase (retain underscores)\nCASE_UPPER = Uppercase (retain underscores)\n{quote}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-08-08T21:55:29.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-08-08T21:55:29.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10715",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I'm renaming this with a suffix of \"Name Filter\", since I expect some sort of filter plugin solution will be used to provide a degree of flexibility in how DB adapters address variances between the names of databases, tables, and columns and the names used by developers in their code.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-08-16T20:19:06.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-08-16T20:19:06.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10776",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Andr\u00e9 Hoffmann wrote:\n> In my opinion it also lacks of prefix support for tables. I myself extended it, but I don't think that I'm the only one using table prefixes. In other words: it would definitely meet the 80-20 rule.\n>\n> On 9\/5\/06, *Victor Bolshov* <vbolshov@rbc.ru <mailto:vbolshov@rbc.ru>> wrote:\n>\n>     I think \"getName()\" should be implemented in Zend_Db_Table. Recently,\n>     I've had a situation where I needed to know the name of the table.\n>     All I\n>     could do was strtolower(get_class($table)) - which is a poor\n>     decision.\n>\n>     Regards, Victor. \n\nPrefixing table names fits in the category of filtering table and column names (the subject of this issue).\n\nAlso, if any name filtering is used, that same code should also contain the logic to retrieve the original table name - the equivalent of getName() in the email above.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-05T22:11:08.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-05T22:11:08.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/11356",
                    "author": {
